05292nam a22008055i 9780812205374DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20112006pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979754110  a97808122053747 a10.9783/97808122053742doi  a(DE-B1597)449330  a(OCoLC)651724417  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHD9999.L853 7aHIS0200002bisacsh04a381/.45687/0945090232221 aStuard, Susan Mosher, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGilding the Market :bLuxury and Fashion in Fourteenth-Century Italy /cSusan Mosher Stuard. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b24 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Middle Ages Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tChapter 1. Introduction -- tChapter 2. Desirable Wares -- tChapter 3. Gravitas and Consumption -- tChapter 4. Curbing Women’s Excesses -- tChapter 5. Costs of Luxuries -- tChapter 6. Shops and Trades -- tChapter 7. Marketmakers -- tChapter 8. Conclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the fourteenth century, garish ornaments, bright colors, gilt, and military effects helped usher in the age of fashion in Italy. Over a short span of years important matters began to turn on the cut of a sleeve. Fashion influenced consumption and provided a stimulus that drove demand for goods and turned wealthy townspeople into enthusiastic consumers. Making wise decisions about the alarmingly expensive goods that composed a fashionable wardrobe became a matter of pressing concern, especially when the market caught on and became awash in cheaper editions of luxury wares.Focusing on the luxury trade in fashionable wear and accessories in Venice, Florence, and other towns in Italy, Gilding the Market investigates a major shift in patterns of consumption at the height of medieval prosperity, which, more remarkably, continued through the subsequent era of plague, return of plague, and increased warfare. A fine sensitivity to the demands of "le pompe," that is, the public display of private wealth, infected town life. The quest for luxuries affected markets by enlarging exchange activity and encouraging retail trades. As both consumers and tradesmen, local goldsmiths, long-distance traders, bankers, and money changers played important roles in creating this new age of fashion.In response to a greater public display of luxury goods, civic sumptuary laws were written to curb spending and extreme fashion, but these were aimed at women, youth, and children, leaving townsmen largely unrestricted in their consumption. With erudition, grace, and an evocative selection of illustrations, some reproduced in full color, Susan Mosher Stuard explores the arrival of fashion in European history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aClothing and dresszItalyxHistoryyMedieval, 500-1500. 0aConsumption (Economics)zItalyxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aFashionzItalyxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aLuxurieszItalyxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aLuxury goods industryzItalyxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aMedieval and Renaissance Studies. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Italy.2bisacsh  aHistory.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package World Historyz978311041347208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220537440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812205374423Coveruhttps://www